  subhead="It is 11am on a Tuesday. You are in the workshop plasma-cutting 10mm mild steel plate — the torch tracing a CAD-guided pattern for a decorative garden screen, the metal glowing orange along the cut line, the extraction fan roaring above you. Two calls come in at 11:15 and 11:45. Your phone is on the bench behind the plasma table — unreachable while the cut is running. Without Missed Call Text Back, both callers hear voicemail. One leaves a message — 'calling about some gates' — the other hangs up and calls the next fabrication workshop on Google. With it, both receive texts within seconds. The first replies: 'Hi — want a pair of estate-style driveway gates in wrought-iron, about 3.8m opening, with matching pedestrian gate and railings either side. Automation too. OX15.' The second: 'We are an architect practice — need a fabricator for a bespoke steel and glass staircase in a residential new-build. Happy to share drawings.' At noon you pause the plasma and check. Two leads — a £12,000 gate and railing package and a potentially £25,000 staircase commission — both with contact details and project context."
